She turned to a blank page and wrote down the date. Below it, she wrote "11/05/648 - 13/12/648."
"Are you rereading memories?" asked Ivory, looking at the old journal. Kari nodded. "Do you think they'll let you out for Christmas? It's only a few days away now."
Kari tapped the lantern twice. No. Ivory was right. The King of Ice never let Kari go out, because in his eyes she was "a mistake." She was born mute, and she was the only girl in the family, which was otherwise composed entirely of boys.
Ivory was one too, in her own way. When she had come out as non-binary, it was as if the world had changed too. She was given tasks that condemned her to solitude, as punishment for her difference.
Iel also had to serve the princess, but that wasn't so bad, because it gave iel a friend.
"It's almost your birthday, I think?" asked Ivory, remembering that the princess's birthday was coming in a few days. Kari nodded, a sad glint in her pale blue eyes.
"Do you want to celebrate it?" As iel asked the question, iel remembered what she had answered last time.
No, Kari brushed it off. Ivory knew it was a difficult subject for her. It was the day she had been locked in her room and her mother had been banished. Ivory was still a baby when it happened, but iel remembered the servants' and inhabitants' outrage. Iel had heard that Queen Eirwen was a good queen, but also had this strange ability to predict the future.
"Well... what do you want to do?" iel asked. Kari looked up with enthusiasm. She handed a piece of paper to Ivory. But when iel looked at it...
Paint canvas 15 cm x 15 cm
White, several shades of blue paint
6 brushes of different sizes
Easel
"Do you want me to find these things for you?" said Ivory, turning to the silent princess who was frantically tapping, shaking her bangs back and forth. "Yes?" iel chuckled slightly, seeing the usually reserved princess get passionate about something. It was the first time she had asked for something unrelated to books and that wasn't in her room.
"Okay. See you later?" offered Ivory, standing up and making their way through the pile of papers and notebooks.
Kari nodded and plunged back into her memories, wrapping herself once again in her thick blanket.
Iel left the room with relief. The princess was finally stepping out of her comfort zone by asking for things that were not her usual domain, like paint.
Iel turned back through the corridors, trying not to listen to the whispers of the maids.
"I heard she's possessed by Queen Eirwen, that's why she always goes into that room."
"I heard she eats children in that room."
"She looks like a man, right?"
Iel covered their ears, because trying to ignore them wasn't working. Iel headed toward the royal painter's room, which was in the east wing, second door on the left.
Ivory approached the door, which was just as ornate as Kari's. It featured a white dragon, one of the six primordial dragons, who, according to legend, had created Frostfell. It was normal for the painter to display it on his door. He loved the story.
Iel opened the door, expecting to find a normal scene. Paint splatters everywhere, pencils and papers scattered around the room, easels covering every last centimeter of wall. Surprisingly, iel saw none of this. The room was clean and there was a red velvet backdrop with a stool right in front of it. On the stool stood Prince Aquilo, who was having his portrait painted.
"Ah, hello, Ivory! You come to watch your future king pose for a portrait?" Aquilo asked Ivory, giving them a wink.
"Pardon, petit prince," he replied, partially ignoring her, in search of the items her silent friend desired. "I'm here just to get supplies."
"Ah, is the girl going to leave very soon?" asked Aquilo, "But I wanted to see you!"
"Well, not me." Ivory had found the art supplies on her list and placed them in a box that they had found. "And I am not a girl."
The prince had not thought of that however. "Oh my dear, you know well that it's just a phase! It will pass when you grow up!" he muttered.
"I have to go," they said, suddenly uncomfortable, because of the prince's words, which reminded them of all the bad things people said about their gender identity. I really want to get away from him.
"Are you leaving already?" The Prince appeared immediately at the door, ignoring the royal painter's complaints.
"That's not the behavior of a future king!" iel scolded.
"No one will know. The others won't believe you, and the painter won't say anything if he values his life." He turned to the painter for a second, then leaned toward Ivory. "What would you say to a romantic appointment?" Iel shuddered. Indeed, iel had received many threats in the past, but never from a prince, much less the heir to the throne.
"Don't you know what the word no means?" iel said, pushing the prince aside.
"Hé no," replied Aquilo with a smile. Obviously, the prince who gets everything he wants doesn't know what this word means.
Ivory rolled their eyes. "Why want a romantic appointment with me rather than with others? You must have a good hundred suitors?"
He interrupted them, still smiling: "500, to be exact." He flung his hair back, making it fly through the cold air.
"So, why me rather than another? I am the palace's threat." Iel wrapped their arms around their body.
"You are the most beautiful girl I have ever seen." Aquilo placed his finger under their chin and forced Ivory to look at him.
